<n-docbody><doc bill="Y"><content.metadata.block><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.second.line.cite><bop/><bos/>Ga. Evidence § 1:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.second.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block><prop.block><prop.head toc-guid=""><bop/><bos/><headtext>Agnor&apos;s Georgia Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head><content.metadata.block><cmd.dates><cmd.currency.default iso.d="20191101"><bop/><bos/>November 2019 Update<eos/><eop/></cmd.currency.default></cmd.dates></content.metadata.block><author.line><bop/><bos/><author>Ana Marcela Rountree</author><eos/><eop/></author.line><prop.head toc-guid="I25526100630a11eab5989292d3e01631"><bop/><bos/><label.name>Chapter</label.name><label.designator>1.</label.designator><headtext>Introduction and History</headtext><eos/><eop/></prop.head></prop.block><message.block><include.copyright n-include_collection="w_wlnv_msg" n-include_guid="I1DA35ED81DD211B281BAD200220BDFCA">Copr. (C) West 2005 No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. Works</include.copyright></message.block><section><section.front><doc.title toc-guid="Id71f05a1682311ea83aee46e6decbb85"><head parent="doc.title"><bop/><bos/><label.name>§ </label.name><label.designator>1:1.</label.designator><headtext>Purpose and construction of the Rules of Evidence</headtext><eos/><eop/></head></doc.title></section.front><section.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>In 1851, Judge Lumpkin defined evidence as <begin.quote ID="QT_0001"/>“the means by which any fact which is put in issue is established or disproved.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0001"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I75fd56c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">1</footnote.reference>] Georgia enacted its first Code of Evidence in 1863.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>Generally, any evidence that is relevant to a material issue in the case is admissible unless there is some specific rule excluding it. <eos/><bos/>Most rules of evidence developed as exclusionary rules, but the trend today is in favor of admissibility. <eos/><bos/><cite.query w-src-number="0287018071" w-seq-number="00002" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-1-1" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I8a4b5b5074d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-1-1</cite.query> states, <begin.quote ID="QT_0002"/>“The object of all legal investigation is the discovery of truth. <eos/><bos/>Rules of evidence shall be construed to secure fairness in administration, eliminate unjustifiable expense and delay, and promote the growth and development of the law of evidence to the end that the truth may be ascertained and proceedings justly determined.”<eos/><end.quote refid="QT_0002"/></paratext><eop/></para><para><bop/><bos/><paratext>The underlying principle of Georgia evidence law is that evidence of doubtful relevance <begin.quote ID="QT_0004"/>“should be admitted and its weight and effect should be left for a jury determination.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0004"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I75fdcbf074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5">2</footnote.reference>] Balanced against this principle is the rule that a trial court may exclude relevant evidence <begin.quote ID="QT_0003"/>“if its probative value is substantially outweighed by the danger of unfair prejudice, confusion of the issues, or misleading the jury, or by considerations of undue delay, waste of time, or needless presentation of cumulative evidence.”<eos/><bos/><end.quote refid="QT_0003"/>[<footnote.reference refid="I75fdf30074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><?page no="1"?>3</footnote.reference>]</paratext><eos/><eop/></para></section.body></section><footnote.block><footnote ID="I75fd56c074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>1</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018071" w-serial-number="1851001238" w-seq-number="00001" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000359" w-pinpoint-page="567" ID="I8a4a980174d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Hotchkiss v. Newton, 10 Ga. 560, 567, 1851 WL 1411 (1851)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I75fdcbf074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator>2</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018071" w-serial-number="1991113951" w-seq-number="00003" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I8a4bd08274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Peppers v. State, 261 Ga. 338, 339, 404 S.E.2d 788 (1991)</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote><footnote ID="I75fdf30074d311ea92c4fb7908f1a7b5"><label.designator><?page no="1"?>3</label.designator><footnote.body><para><bop/><?page no="1"?><bos/><paratext><cite.query w-src-number="0287018071" w-serial-number="1991124044" w-seq-number="00004" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I8a4c6cc274d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">Zant v. Foster, 261 Ga. 450, 451, 406 S.E.2d 74 (1991)</cite.query> (<case.history>overruled on other grounds by</case.history>, <cite.query w-src-number="0287018071" w-serial-number="1992112178" w-seq-number="00005" w-ref-type="RP" w-pub-number="0000711" ID="I8a4c6cc574d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">State v. Patillo, 262 Ga. 259, 417 S.E.2d 139 (1992)</cite.query>).<eos/><bos/> See also <cite.query w-src-number="0287018071" w-seq-number="00006" w-ref-type="LQ" w-normalized-cite="GAST24-4-403" w-pub-number="1000468" ID="I8a4c6cc674d211eab2f0b920da2605c5">O.C.G.A. § 24-4-403</cite.query>.<eos/></paratext><eop/></para></footnote.body></footnote></footnote.block><content.metadata.block><cmd.royalty><cmd.copyright><bop/><bos/>Westlaw. © 2019 Thomson Reuters.  <eos/><bos/>No Claim to Orig. U.S. Govt. <eos/><bos/>Works.<eos/><eop/></cmd.copyright></cmd.royalty><cmd.identifiers><cmd.cites><cmd.first.line.cite><bop/><bos/>GAEVIDENCE § 1:1<eos/><eop/></cmd.first.line.cite></cmd.cites></cmd.identifiers></content.metadata.block></doc></n-docbody>
